replies.bodyText:
An energy meter is a perfect example for a COUNTER. If you get 34567.122 kWh, multiply by thousand and store in a COUNTER.
@kaikreuzer yes. But I was not only thinking of outliers but of values that have a large statistical variance. Imagine someone (not me but I‘ve seen people use that) who meters radioactivity. He will for sure not store the total number of counts (That‘s a useless value, If total dose matters we have other problems than data storage.), he wants to store „per time“. So his unit would be Bequerel and measure every minute. Each of these values will be very different (because count rate is low in any case). The average is a much better aggregation than last value, and that is true after an hour.
This is also true for fast changing temperatures (like central heating boiler temperature). Aggregating over an 15 minutes might lose turn-ons (turns on immediately at the beginning, runs for 5 minutes, temperature is nearly back to normal after 15 minutes, when the next LAST value is taken).

